00:36:03.170 --> 00:36:06.090
And then just be ready for
that and see what you can do.

00:36:06.090 --> 00:36:06.930
It's cool.

00:36:06.930 --> 00:36:12.360
What tips do you have for a
first time Tango developer?

00:36:12.360 --> 00:36:14.440
JESSE SHELL: Oh, I've got a lot.

00:36:19.420 --> 00:36:22.640
The big thing is
to keep it simple.

00:36:22.640 --> 00:36:26.400
You're going to have to
find your way in terms

00:36:26.400 --> 00:36:27.770
of what works.

00:36:27.770 --> 00:36:31.110
You're going to have a lot
of big dreamy ideas about all

00:36:31.110 --> 00:36:33.040
the wonderful things
that are going to work.

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:36.720
And not everything
is going to work yet.

00:36:36.720 --> 00:36:39.820
It's a platform that
has its strengths

00:36:39.820 --> 00:36:41.580
and has its weaknesses.

00:36:41.580 --> 00:36:45.170
If you go in-- and I think
we did this initially.

00:36:45.170 --> 00:36:48.580
We started playing
around with it 18 months

00:36:48.580 --> 00:36:50.420
or two years ago--
something like that.

00:36:50.420 --> 00:36:52.920
And we had this big
dream of exactly how

00:36:52.920 --> 00:36:53.800
it was going to work.

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:55.508
And when it didn't
work exactly that way,

00:36:55.508 --> 00:36:57.327
we we're like we hate this.

00:36:57.327 --> 00:36:59.160
And then a little later,
we were like, well,

00:36:59.160 --> 00:37:01.540
maybe we should just
do what it's good at.

00:37:01.540 --> 00:37:04.590
And then we started
focusing on that,

00:37:04.590 --> 00:37:09.870
and then we started making
all of this path forward.

00:37:09.870 --> 00:37:11.860
So I think going in
with an open mind

00:37:11.860 --> 00:37:15.600
and looking for what it's good
at, and you'll find things.

00:37:15.600 --> 00:37:18.004
Like we ended up
finding oh my god,

00:37:18.004 --> 00:37:19.420
it's really good
at playing Jenga.

00:37:19.420 --> 00:37:21.830
And this just hadn't
occurred to anybody,

00:37:21.830 --> 00:37:27.580
but it was because we started
thinking where is this strong

00:37:27.580 --> 00:37:28.970
and what can it do?

00:37:28.970 --> 00:37:30.490
ROBIN HUNICKE: I
would say also just

00:37:30.490 --> 00:37:34.790
really being open to trying
the weirdest and most bizarre

00:37:34.790 --> 00:37:36.820
idea that you have.

00:37:36.820 --> 00:37:39.727
Keita is incredibly irreverent
when it comes to reality.

00:37:39.727 --> 00:37:41.810
He just doesn't like the
fact that there's gravity

00:37:41.810 --> 00:37:43.779
and that we have limitations
of physical bodies

00:37:43.779 --> 00:37:45.570
and that we can't just
appear to each other

00:37:45.570 --> 00:37:49.290
as giant Teddy Bears or
animating carrots or whatever.

00:37:49.290 --> 00:37:51.790
He wants the world to be a
really magical place in ways

00:37:51.790 --> 00:37:53.581
that are sometimes very
frustrating to him.

00:37:53.581 --> 00:37:55.740
So his first
experience with Tango

00:37:55.740 --> 00:37:58.850
was to immediately ask can we
hang things on the ceiling?

00:37:58.850 --> 00:38:00.670
Can I make a cloud
that will rain

00:38:00.670 --> 00:38:02.960
and then little
flowers will sprout?

00:38:02.960 --> 00:38:06.490
How can I engage in this reality
in a way that totally questions

00:38:06.490 --> 00:38:07.520
what we expect?

00:38:07.520 --> 00:38:09.790
And so to give
yourself permission

00:38:09.790 --> 00:38:13.260
to just have the strange idea
and put it in, because it

00:38:13.260 --> 00:38:16.130
is so easy, it is so fast.

00:38:16.130 --> 00:38:19.780
It was so possible for us
to add features and get them

00:38:19.780 --> 00:38:23.860
into the pipeline and testable
within the same day of having

00:38:23.860 --> 00:38:24.360
a meeting.

00:38:24.360 --> 00:38:27.060
It would be in the device.

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:29.570
And so don't lock
yourself into this pattern

00:38:29.570 --> 00:38:31.760
of thinking you have
to flow everything out.

00:38:31.760 --> 00:38:33.850
Really go with what the
device is good with,

00:38:33.850 --> 00:38:37.530
but specifically, ask
yourself, why not as opposed

00:38:37.530 --> 00:38:40.800
to sort of always trying
to detail exactly why.

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:43.050
JOEL PENNINGTON: And
then give it to people

00:38:43.050 --> 00:38:44.910
and watch them play with it.

00:38:44.910 --> 00:38:48.400
That's the most amazing reaction
because they start small,

00:38:48.400 --> 00:38:51.106
and then once they
realize what they can do,

00:38:51.106 --> 00:38:52.480
you'll never get
the tablet back.

00:38:52.480 --> 00:38:53.830
You're just going to have
to go buy another one.

00:38:53.830 --> 00:38:54.790
ROBIN HUNICKE: It's true.

00:38:54.790 --> 00:38:55.290
It's true.

00:38:55.290 --> 00:38:58.340
We're always having people
jealous of people interacting

00:38:58.340 --> 00:39:00.380
with the Tango device at work.

00:39:00.380 --> 00:39:02.800
People cluster around
and try to touch it.

00:39:02.800 --> 00:39:06.310
KYLE NEL: And to add onto that,
it's been really helpful for us

00:39:06.310 --> 00:39:08.710
after you hand somebody--
a normal person who

00:39:08.710 --> 00:39:11.680
doesn't do this all the time
and have them experience it,

00:39:11.680 --> 00:39:15.160
have them explain it to somebody
else sitting right next to them

00:39:15.160 --> 00:39:16.702
about how they
would talk about it.

00:39:16.702 --> 00:39:18.910
There's so many different
things that came out of it.

00:39:18.910 --> 00:39:20.859
Like, oh my gosh, I never
even-- that's really

00:39:20.859 --> 00:39:21.900
what you got out of that?

00:39:21.900 --> 00:39:23.316
And that's really
what you wanted?

00:39:23.316 --> 00:39:26.797
And it just takes you
in different directions.

00:39:26.797 --> 00:39:28.380
KELLY SANTIAGO: Yeah,
you were talking

00:39:28.380 --> 00:39:31.980
earlier, Robin, before
the panel about designing

00:39:31.980 --> 00:39:33.131
around the constraints.

00:39:33.131 --> 00:39:35.380
And Jesse was kind of touching
on this too-- there are

00:39:35.380 --> 00:39:37.790
strengths and there
are weaknesses.

00:39:37.790 --> 00:39:40.210
And so when you find out maybe
that original idea doesn't

00:39:40.210 --> 00:39:42.847
quite work, OK,
well, how can I lean

00:39:42.847 --> 00:39:44.680
into what the strengths
of the platform are?

00:39:44.680 --> 00:39:47.070
ROBIN HUNICKE: Yeah, I
think that we actually

00:39:47.070 --> 00:39:51.100
felt comfortable
rolling our own when

00:39:51.100 --> 00:39:53.240
it came to certain
aspects of the system.

00:39:53.240 --> 00:39:56.171
We especially wanted people to
be able to set up a little play

00:39:56.171 --> 00:39:58.420
area and then walk away from
it and come back and have

00:39:58.420 --> 00:39:59.400
it persist.

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:01.817
So we were able to use
features of the device

00:40:01.817 --> 00:40:02.650
to make that happen.

00:40:02.650 --> 00:40:05.520
And then in places where we
were struggling a little bit,

00:40:05.520 --> 00:40:07.762
we just wrote software that
took care of that problem

00:40:07.762 --> 00:40:08.970
from a different perspective.

00:40:08.970 --> 00:40:11.240
So we would ask ourselves
what is this really about?

00:40:11.240 --> 00:40:13.304
So for example, being
able to leave a place

00:40:13.304 --> 00:40:14.720
and then come back
to it is really

00:40:14.720 --> 00:40:17.899
about matching the picture in
your mind to what you built.

00:40:17.899 --> 00:40:20.190
So we built something where
you take a picture with it,

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:21.880
and then later, you just
line up the picture,

00:40:21.880 --> 00:40:22.890
and it's there again.

00:40:22.890 --> 00:40:25.370
And people will do a lot.

00:40:25.370 --> 00:40:27.620
They will give
you a lot in order

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:29.104
to have that fun experience.

00:40:29.104 --> 00:40:31.270
They haven't learned that
the technology is supposed

00:40:31.270 --> 00:40:33.000
to solve all of our problems.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:35.570
When we first started working
with Tango developers,

00:40:35.570 --> 00:40:36.600
Nick [INAUDIBLE] and
some of the other people

00:40:36.600 --> 00:40:38.790
that we were working
with in the organization

00:40:38.790 --> 00:40:41.090
gave us this big, long
list of all these things

00:40:41.090 --> 00:40:43.930
that we would have to
educate users to do.

00:40:43.930 --> 00:40:47.780
And I said, do you want me to
write you a use case tutorial

00:40:47.780 --> 00:40:49.405
or do you want to game design?

00:40:49.405 --> 00:40:52.677
Because I can design around
like 30% to 70% of these things

00:40:52.677 --> 00:40:55.010
depending on how creative the
people are on the project.

00:40:55.010 --> 00:40:57.630
Let's not think about all the
limitations of the technology,

00:40:57.630 --> 00:40:59.755
let's think about the couple
of things it does well

00:40:59.755 --> 00:41:02.020
and what we can get people
to give us for free.

00:41:02.020 --> 00:41:04.061
And so that's the other
thing that you can really

00:41:04.061 --> 00:41:07.250
do with something this simple
is you can get a lot for free.

00:41:07.250 --> 00:41:08.850
People are not
expecting the world

00:41:08.850 --> 00:41:11.100
to be given to
them on a platter,

00:41:11.100 --> 00:41:14.970
and honestly, our user
testing on Google Campus,

00:41:14.970 --> 00:41:17.470
when people experience
it, they're blown away.

00:41:17.470 --> 00:41:19.980
They're literally
like, this is so cool.

00:41:19.980 --> 00:41:21.550
It does so much cool stuff.

00:41:21.550 --> 00:41:22.860
I had no idea.

00:41:22.860 --> 00:41:26.720
And in your mind as a developer,
you're imagining the holodeck.

00:41:26.720 --> 00:41:29.110
So you're like, it's
not the holodeck.

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:32.760
This is not Data doing
a Sherlock Holmes

00:41:32.760 --> 00:41:34.460
thing in real time.

00:41:34.460 --> 00:41:38.350
Your limitations are so
much greater than the user.

00:41:38.350 --> 00:41:40.970
The everyday person
who picks up a Tango

00:41:40.970 --> 00:41:43.430
will literally be blown
away, so don't limit yourself

00:41:43.430 --> 00:41:44.696
in that way.

00:41:44.696 --> 00:41:46.820
KELLY SANTIAGO: So we just
have a few minutes left.

00:41:46.820 --> 00:41:48.840
I'm wondering if real
quickly we can put back

00:41:48.840 --> 00:41:51.490
the slide with the
speaker's information on it

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:53.970
and you can see their
Twitter accounts.

00:41:53.970 --> 00:41:56.290
Let's give a hand for
all our awesome panelists

00:41:56.290 --> 00:41:57.570
and developers.

00:41:57.570 --> 00:41:59.580
Thank you for sharing
your lessons learned

00:41:59.580 --> 00:42:00.580
and for coming out here.

